<h2 class="govuk-heading-l" id="anomalies">Known anomalies</h2>

<div class="govuk-warning-text">
    <span class="govuk-warning-text__icon" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
    <strong class="govuk-warning-text__text">
        <span class="govuk-visually-hidden">Warning</span>
        These are documented mismatches between what the code expects and
        what is wired up today. None of them are necessarily bugs &mdash;
        they may be intentional or pending cleanup &mdash; but they are
        traps for anyone reading the source for the first time.
    </strong>
</div>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="anomaly-a11y"><code>AccessibilityAdministrator</code> role is checked but never granted</h3>
<p class="govuk-body">
    Checks: <code>Controllers/AccessibilityController.cs:2294</code>,
    <code>Views/Apps/Accessibility/_Statement.cshtml:69,314</code>,
    <code>Views/Apps/Accessibility/_Settings.cshtml:107</code>.
</p>
<p class="govuk-body">
    No code in the repo grants this role. <code>EnsureCompassUserMiddleware</code>
    only emits <code>Admin / SuperAdmin / Reporter / Visitor</code>, and there
    is no Entra app-role-to-claim mapping in <code>Program.cs</code>. Either
    Entra is configured externally to emit a <code>roles</code> claim with
    this value, or the check is dead. Confirm with the team before relying
    on it.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="anomaly-dual-admin">Two parallel admin UIs for groups</h3>
<p class="govuk-body">
    Legacy <code>/Admin/UserManagement/...</code>
    (<code>Controllers/Admin/GroupManagementController.cs</code> +
    <code>Views/Admin/GroupManagement/*.cshtml</code>) and modern
    <code>/modern/admin/groups/...</code>
    (<code>Controllers/Modern/ModernAdminController.cs:1061-1322</code> +
    <code>Views/Modern/Admin/Group{Create,Edit,Detail}.cshtml</code>) both
    target the same DB tables. Send new users to the modern surface.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="anomaly-require-feature"><code>RequireFeaturePermissionAttribute</code> is unused</h3>
<p class="govuk-body">
    <code>Attributes/RequireFeaturePermissionAttribute.cs</code> is fully
    implemented but referenced by zero actions. The
    <code>GroupFeaturePermissions</code> table is exercised today only
    via <code>IPermissionService.HasPermissionAsync</code> in admin-UI
    helpers, not as a per-action gate.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="anomaly-user-role"><code>User.Role</code> is effectively read-only</h3>
<p class="govuk-body">
    New users default to <code>Visitor</code> in all five entry points
    (<code>EnsureCompassUserMiddleware.cs:69</code>,
    <code>PermissionService.cs:195</code>,
    <code>GroupManagementController.cs:517</code>,
    <code>AdminController.cs:320</code>, <code>Program.cs:5284</code>).
    No UI surface mutates the field. The three
    <code>[Authorize(Roles = "Admin,SuperAdmin")]</code> attributes in the
    codebase therefore admit only the seeded super-admin user unless
    operators have manually updated rows via SQL. Treat the
    <code>Role</code> enum as deprecated in favour of groups.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="anomaly-spellings"><code>User.IsInRole</code> spelling defence</h3>
<p class="govuk-body">
    <code>Views/Shared/_TopNav.cshtml:115-125</code> checks six spellings
    of the admin claim (<code>"super_admin"</code>, <code>"admin"</code>,
    <code>"Super admin"</code>, <code>"SuperAdmin"</code>, <code>"Admin"</code>,
    <code>"Super Admin"</code>) and additionally treats any claim containing
    both <code>"super"</code> and <code>"admin"</code> case-insensitively as
    admin. The middleware only ever emits canonical spellings
    (<code>"Admin"</code>, <code>"SuperAdmin"</code>); the extras are
    defensive code against an Entra mapping that was never wired up.
</p>

